sigp= scipy.stats.norm.isf(stats.poisson.sf(20100, mu=20000))
print("The significance of observing Higgs (significance of measuring Nqcd+Nhiggs) is {:.2f}.".format(sigp))

In [41]:
sigc=100/(np.sqrt(20000))
print("𝑁𝐻𝑖𝑔𝑔𝑠/(√𝑁𝑄𝐶𝐷) = {:.2f}".format(sigc))

𝑁𝐻𝑖𝑔𝑔𝑠/(√𝑁𝑄𝐶𝐷) = 0.71

The signifance calculated form Poisson statistics is very close to number of 𝑁𝐻𝑖𝑔𝑔𝑠/(√𝑁𝑄𝐶𝐷). They only differ by 0.1. We know from Central Limiting Theorem that as the mean value increases, the Poisson distribution approaches a Gaussian distribution. This tells us that the distribution is very close to a Gaussian distribution, and we may use 𝑁𝐻𝑖𝑔𝑔𝑠/(√𝑁𝑄𝐶𝐷) to approximate significance.

In [42]:
cuts= np.linspace(120,max(higgs['mass']),10)

for i in range(len(cuts)):
    counth=0
    countq=0
    for j in range(len(higgs['mass'])):
        if higgs['mass'][j] <= cuts[i]:
            counth+=1
        if qcd['mass'][j] <= cuts[i]:
            countq+=1
    print("mass cut: {:.2f}".format(cuts[i])) 
    Ncounth=counth*100/100000
    Ncountq=countq*20000/100000
    sig=Ncounth/(np.sqrt(Ncountq))
    print("𝑁𝐻𝑖𝑔𝑔𝑠/(√𝑁𝑄𝐶𝐷): {:.2f}".format(sig))
    i+=1

Evaluate observed significance and compare your results to expectation¶

In [67]:
Ncounth=len(higgsl_masked)*(100/20000)*(4060/100000)
Ncountq=len(qcdl_masked)*(4060/100000)
Ncountd=len(dtl_masked)
sig_ex=Ncounth/(np.sqrt(Ncountq))
sig_ob=Ncounth/(np.sqrt(Ncountd))
print("After optimal selection, the expected significance 𝑁𝐻𝑖𝑔𝑔𝑠/(√𝑁𝑄𝐶𝐷) is {:.2f}".format(sig_ex))
print("After optimal selection, the observed significance 𝑁𝐻𝑖𝑔𝑔𝑠/(√𝑁𝑄𝐶𝐷) is {:.2f}".format(sig_ob))

After optimal selection, the expected significance 𝑁𝐻𝑖𝑔𝑔𝑠/(√𝑁𝑄𝐶𝐷) is 4.05
After optimal selection, the observed significance 𝑁𝐻𝑖𝑔𝑔𝑠/(√𝑁𝑄𝐶𝐷) is 2.79

The observed siginifance is smaller than expected significance.

95% Confidence Level of signal yields¶

In the low luminosity data, the observed significance is less than 5 𝜎 . We will calculate the 95% confidence level upper limit of signal yield.¶
Evaluate the expected and the observed 95% confidence level upper limit¶
In [80]:
expected_yield= (stats.poisson.ppf(0.95, mu=20100))-20000
print("For low luminosity data, the expected 95% confidence level upper limit is {:.2f}".format(expected_yield))

For low luminosity data, the expected 95% confidence level upper limit is 333.00
In [77]:
observed_yield= (stats.poisson.ppf(0.95, mu=4060+(4060*(100/20000))))-(4060)
print("For low luminosity data, the observed 95% confidence level upper limit is {:.2f}".format(observed_yield))

For low luminosity data, the observed 95% confidence level upper limit is 126.00

95% confidence level upper limit is the value than which the signals will be smaller 95% of the times. Here the observed significance is smaller than the expected because the expected yield is 20100, and the observed is 4060 which is much smaller. Comparing the posisson distributions
